## The Grade Inversion

In natural diamonds, D is the rarest color grade. IF and FL are the rarest clarity grades. A 2ct natural D-IF emerald cut would cost well over $60,000 — a stone reserved for private collections and investment portfolios, not everyday wear.

In lab-grown, [D-FL at 2ct costs $4,735](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28828463?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

This is the grade inversion. In natural diamonds, buyers at a $20,000–$30,000 budget must compromise. They take F or G color instead of D. They take VS1 or VS2 instead of IF or FL. Because the top grades at 2ct in natural are financially out of reach for most buyers. In lab, the top grades are not just accessible — they are the most common options at 2ct. D-FL is entry-level, not premium.

The practical consequence for the emerald cut specifically: the step-cut clarity tax disappears in lab at 2ct. In natural, you choose clarity carefully because SI1 is risky and VS2 is borderline, and every grade improvement costs real money. In lab, D-FL for $4,735 means you start with the best clarity grade available. There is no clarity trade-off to make.

The grade inversion also applies to color. In natural, going from G to F at 2ct emerald cut adds hundreds to thousands of dollars. In lab, D costs $4,735 for 2ct. You do not compromise on color in lab at this weight either.

![lab grown emerald cut diamond price chart](/images/lab-grown-emerald-cut-diamond-price-chart.avif)

The one thing the grade inversion does not provide: natural origin. A lab diamond and a natural diamond are chemically identical — both are pure carbon in a crystal lattice. But the natural stone formed in the earth over billions of years under extreme heat and pressure. That origin carries its own value for buyers who want it. No lab equivalent can replicate it.

For buyers who do not place a premium on origin, the grade inversion at 2ct makes lab the unambiguous choice on every measurable value metric. You get better color, better clarity, the same size, and spend less than 20% of the natural price. The step-cut's open facets will display that D-FL grade exactly as clearly as they would display the F-VS1 natural — which is why buying the best clarity grade in lab is not a splurge, it is the baseline.

