## What to Check Before Buying a 2 Carat Emerald Cut Diamond

Buying a 2ct emerald cut from certified market inventory is not the same as buying a brilliant-cut diamond from a data sheet. The step-cut's transparent facets mean the certificate and the actual stone can tell different stories. Four things to verify before committing at $4,700–$24,000.

**Proportion check.** Confirm the length-to-width ratio and the exact millimeter dimensions. "2.00ct emerald cut" describes weight, not shape character. A 2ct stone at 9.5mm × 6.7mm is a very different stone than 9mm × 7mm, even though both weigh 2ct. The 1.29–1.35 L/W range is the classic emerald cut. Outside that range is a style preference, but know what you are buying.

**Depth percentage.** For an emerald cut, depth of 60–70% is the standard range. Below 60%, the stone looks glassy and shallow — the hall-of-mirrors effect collapses because the facet depth is insufficient to create layered reflections. Above 72%, the stone looks dark and loses face-up presence. At 2ct, depth percentage matters more than in a brilliant cut where the facets do more optical work.

**Fluorescence.** A 2ct natural emerald cut with strong blue fluorescence can appear hazy in daylight conditions. For a transparent step-cut stone, fluorescence haze is more visible than in a brilliant-cut stone because there is no scattering from complex faceting. Faint or none is safer at this price level. In lab diamonds, fluorescence is rare and typically not listed.

**Video, not just images.** The emerald cut's step facets are responsive to lighting and angle in ways that still photography cannot capture. A bright studio photo can make an SI1 look clean. A 360° video under real lighting shows exactly what you get. At $4,700–$24,000, always watch the video before buying.

